    difficulty: "Beginner",
    body: "Many older adults dismiss the idea of writing a memoir as a project for famous people or polished writers. That belief misses what the work actually does. Life review, the structured looking-back at your own life, is one of the most studied non-medication interventions for older adults in the entire field of geriatric psychology. The psychiatrist Robert Butler first described life review in 1963, and decades of research since have shown that reflecting on and recording your life story improves mood, reduces depressive symptoms, sharpens memory, and increases what researchers call ego integrity, the feeling that your life had shape and meaning.\n\nA 2020 meta-analysis in the journal Aging and Mental Health pulled together 128 studies on reminiscence therapy and life review. The findings were consistent. Older adults who took part in structured life review reported lower depression scores, higher life satisfaction, and improved sense of self compared to control groups. The effect held across cultures, across ages from 60 to 95, and across formats: spoken, written, group, or solo. The act of organizing your past into a coherent narrative is the active ingredient.\n\nThe benefits do not stop with you. Family research from Emory University has tracked what happens when grandparents share their life stories with grandchildren. Children who know their family stories, in particular the stories of how the family overcame hardship, score higher on measures of self-esteem, resilience, and emotional well-being. The researchers called this the do-you-know scale. It turns out that growing up with a sense of belonging to a larger story is one of the strongest predictors of how children handle stress. Your memoir is more than a gift to yourself. It is a kind of inheritance no will or trust can replicate.\n\nThere is also a practical layer. As you and your generation pass on, the details that only you remember go with you. Where your parents were born. What your father did during the war. The name of the dog you had as a child. The recipe your grandmother never wrote down. The reason you left your hometown. Family historians and genealogists describe this as the silent loss, and they say it is the single biggest hole in family history work. Writing it down, even in rough form, closes that gap.\n\nFinally, the writing itself is a form of meaning-making. Many older adults find that telling the story of a hard chapter, a divorce, a war, a child who died, a marriage that worked despite the odds, gives them a kind of peace that years of silence did not. The story becomes a thing outside of you. You can look at it. You can decide what it meant. You can put it away and pick it back up. That is what the research calls narrative integration, and it is one of the most powerful tools older adults have for facing the later years with calm.\n\n(Sources: Butler, R. The Life Review: An Interpretation of Reminiscence in the Aged, Psychiatry 1963; Westerhof, G. and Bohlmeijer, E. Celebrating fifty years of research and applications in reminiscence and life review, Journal of Aging Studies 2014; Duke, M. and Fivush, R. Do You Know? Family Narrative Project, Emory University; Aging and Mental Health 2020 meta-analysis on reminiscence interventions)",
