    body: "The hardest part of memoir is starting. The second hardest part is keeping going. Three subscription services have built their entire businesses around solving both of those problems for older adults and their families. Each one sends you a question once a week for a full year, collects your written or spoken answers, and at the end prints a real hardcover book of your life story. The services differ in format and price, but they share the same insight: a structured question is much easier to answer than a blank page.\n\nStoryWorth was the first of these services and remains the most popular as of 2026. It costs around 99 dollars for a one-year subscription. Each week, an email arrives in your inbox with a single question. Common questions include: What was your father like? What is one of the bravest things you have ever done? Describe your childhood home in detail. You reply by email with your answer, in whatever length feels right, from one paragraph to ten pages. The questions can be selected by you, by the family member who gave you the subscription, or chosen randomly from StoryWorth's library of hundreds. At the end of 52 weeks, your answers are printed in a keepsake hardcover book and shipped to your door. Most subscribers print extra copies for children and grandchildren at around 39 dollars each.\n\nRemento is the newer service and has built its product around voice instead of typing. The price is similar, in the 99 to 199 dollar range depending on the plan. Each week, Remento calls your phone or sends an app notification with a question. You answer by speaking. The Remento app transcribes your voice into clean written text using artificial intelligence, then lets you edit before approving. At the end of the year, the bound book includes both the written transcript and a QR code on each page that, when scanned, plays back the original audio in your own voice. For older adults who find typing painful or who have arthritis, Remento removes the keyboard from the equation entirely. The voice-plus-QR-code feature is also moving for family members, especially after the writer passes on.\n\nStoried Life, formerly known as LifeBio, is the third option and the one most often used by senior living communities, assisted living facilities, and family historians. The service offers more flexibility on schedule. You can answer questions weekly, monthly, or at your own pace. The cost is variable, from around 80 dollars for a basic plan up to 200 for the deluxe with editor review. Storied Life puts more emphasis on family history and genealogy questions, including questions about ancestors, immigration stories, and family traditions, which makes it a good fit for older adults who want their book to lean toward family history rather than personal memoir.\n\nAll three services are popular as gifts. The most common gift pattern is an adult child paying for a parent's subscription for a birthday, Father's Day, or Mother's Day, then receiving a printed copy at the end of the year. This pattern works because the structure removes the resistance: the older parent does not have to think about what to write. They just answer the question of the week. By the end of the year, a book exists that would never have been written otherwise.\n\nBefore signing up, consider three things. First, how does the older adult prefer to communicate? Email and typing favor StoryWorth. Speaking favors Remento. Flexibility favors Storied Life. Second, who selects the questions? If you want the gift-giver to choose, all three allow that. If you want the writer to choose, all three allow that too. Third, who keeps the rights to the content? In all three services, the writer owns their words, and the content can be downloaded as a digital file at any time. You are not locked in.\n\n(Sources: StoryWorth — storyworth.com FAQ and pricing 2026; Remento — remento.co official site; Storied — storied.com formerly LifeBio; AARP product reviews of memoir gift services 2025)",
